```suggestion
export async function withInboxMutationLock<T>(
  target: InboxMutationTarget,
  operation: () => Promise<T>,
  deps: InboxLockDeps = {},
): Promise<T> {
  let lockHandle: Awaited<ReturnType<typeof open>> | undefined;

  try {
    lockHandle = await open(lockPath, "wx");
  } catch (error) {
    if (isLockAlreadyHeldError(error)) {
      throw new Error(buildLockErrorMessage(target));
    }

    throw error;
  }

  try {
    return await operation();
  } finally {
    if (lockHandle) {
      await lockHandle.close();
      await rm(lockPath, { force: true });
    }
  }
}
```

</details>

<!-- suggestion_end -->

<details>
<summary>🤖 Prompt for AI Agents</summary>

```
Verify each finding against the current code and only fix it if needed.

In `@src/cli/inbox-lock.ts` around lines 28 - 34, The catch is currently catching
errors from both open(lockPath, "wx") and operation(), which can misclassify an
EEXIST thrown inside operation() as a lock-conflict; change the flow so
open(lockPath, "wx") is awaited inside its own try/catch and only errors from
that call are passed to isLockAlreadyHeldError (use the existing
isLockAlreadyHeldError(lockErr) and buildLockErrorMessage(target) logic), then,
after successful open and storing lockHandle, call operation() outside that
catch (with its own error handling as needed), and ensure any opened lockHandle
is cleaned up on operation failure or before rethrowing. Ensure references to
open, lockHandle, operation, isLockAlreadyHeldError, buildLockErrorMessage,
lockPath, and target are updated accordingly.
```

</details>

